      • equals

        public boolean equals(Object obj)
        Description copied from class: Tree
        Performs a "deep" equality search on the two trees. Checks if both trees have the same number of nodes, and if each node in the tree is equal to one another. Each node in one tree must be a "mirrored" visual placement of another node in the other tree.
        Specified by:
        equals in class Tree<E extends Comparable<E>>
        Returns:
        true if the trees are deeply equal; false otherwise.

      • equals0

        private boolean equals0(BinaryTree.BinaryNode n1,
                        BinaryTree.BinaryNode n2)
        Performs a recursive "deep" equality search on two nodes (each of which should belong to separate trees of the same generic argument types). The first comparison is if both children of both nodes are null, in which case, the nodes themselves are compared. If not, then a bitwise XOR operation is performed on the conditions of the left children and right children of both nodes being null. If either operation results in true, then false is returned (if the right child of n1 is null but the right child of n2 isn't, then there's no reliable way to compare them, and as such invalidates the equality of the comparing trees). If false, then a recursive approach is taken for comparing the children. Starting with the right child and then moving towards the left child. If both of these comparisons result in true, then the nodes themselves are finally compared.
        Parameters:
        n1 - - the node from the first comparing tree.
        n2 - - the node from the second comparing tree.
        Returns:
        true if both trees are completely equal in terms of their nodes; false otherwise.
